19:26.440 --> 19:38.740
Okay. Mr. Ackerman, you're known as quite a fan, but to us collectors,

19:38.960 --> 19:47.680
you're also known as the ultimate collector. When did you start collecting
science fiction, and what was your first goal, and how has that goal changed as

19:47.680 --> 19:59.420
far as what you're trying to collect? Well, in October 1926, when I first saw a
science fiction magazine, I was only nine years old, and I don't believe I

19:59.420 --> 20:09.580
realized the periodicity of publications. I guess I thought it was some kind of
a one-time phenomenon, and there would never be another amazing stories. And it

20:09.580 --> 20:20.100
wasn't until some months later in 1928 that I saw amazing stories again. Then I
caught on to the fact that if I watched the newsstands carefully, about every

20:20.100 --> 20:35.400
four weeks, there would be more manna from heaven. So I read the magazine so
quickly that there was nothing coming along for another month that I would re

20:35.400 --> 20:49.220
-read the stories. So I hung on to the magazines because they were very precious
to me, and before I knew it, my mother said I had 27 of them. And by about 1930,

20:49.380 --> 21:02.920
I probably had around 100 of them. And one mad moment in my life, during the
Depression, my parents persuaded me to sell my magazines in order to finance new

21:02.920 --> 21:13.600
ones, because 25 cents was kind of tough to come by when men were starving on
the streets trying to make a living selling apples for a nickel. Well, I did

21:13.600 --> 21:28.200
sell my collection, such as it was, about 1930. And before their very eyes, my
parents saw me becoming weak and waned and listless and lost my appetite. And

21:28.200 --> 21:38.080
about 48 hours was all I could take of that. So I said, okay, okay, you know, go
and buy your magazines back if they mean so much to you. And from that day to

21:38.080 --> 21:49.160
this, I have never passed by a magazine. I just buy every single science fiction
fantasy magazine as fast as they are published, have a standing order for every

21:49.160 --> 22:02.440
paperback to be sent to me, go through Publishers Weekly every seven days, and
Locus and any source whatsoever that instances fantasy magazines and books, and

22:02.440 --> 22:10.500
send off for all of them. And then I go through catalogs from all over the
world. And constantly mining the past, you would think that someday you'd say,

22:10.580 --> 22:17.680
well, I've got it all, but there just seems to be no end to it. A perfect
example. I went to the World Science Fiction Convention down in Australia,

22:18.280 --> 22:26.920
walked a half a block from my hotel, and saw a science fiction book in a window.
And I said, well, I don't have it. I suppose it was published here in Australia.

22:27.360 --> 22:36.460
But I went in and I found it was published in New York seven years earlier, and
despite every review I'd read and every list I'd looked at, I hadn't known of it

22:36.460 --> 22:49.100
until that moment. So I feel my collection is incomplete if someone who's
looking at it suddenly says, oh, don't you have? And then I've got 300,000

22:49.100 --> 22:58.940
things, but I don't have this one particular magazine or book, so I guess I'll
have to get it. How has where you've housed the collection through the years

22:58.940 --> 23:12.000
changed from your humble beginnings till now? Well, it started out in San
Francisco. I had, down in the basement, my dad built me a little den, and I was

23:12.000 --> 23:22.840
able to keep everything in one very small room. Then when I moved back to Los
Angeles where I was born, I lived with my maternal grandparents, and they had a

23:22.840 --> 23:36.340
rather large apartment plus three garages. That's where I started filling up
garages. Before I knew it, they were full. And in the hallway in my maternal

23:36.340 --> 23:47.720
grandparents' home, I began stacking books up to the ceiling, and they gave me
one bedroom. And pretty soon it was difficult even to get into bed because it

23:47.720 --> 23:58.720
was totally surrounded. I remember Life magazine came to me 30 years ago in
1951, took a photo of me in that bedroom. And in 1951, I finally moved into my

23:58.720 --> 24:11.400
first home. That had 13 rooms and three garages. And when I totaled that, and I
really mean totaled it, used as many drawers as weren't absolutely necessary for

24:11.400 --> 24:20.260
clothing. They had books and magazines and put them under the beds. And we
didn't need all the bathrooms, so I filled those. And finally, when my wife, the

24:20.260 --> 24:29.360
university professor and science fiction translator, came home and looked in the
refrigerator one day and found the food was gone, replaced by reels of science

24:29.360 --> 24:39.440
fiction movies, she realized the end had come for that home. So for a couple of
years, we lived in an apartment while I used a 13-room home and three garages

24:39.440 --> 24:51.500
totally for my collection. We started all over again eight years ago with a four
-story, 17-room home and the usual three garages. And now that's bursting at the

24:51.500 --> 25:01.300
seams, and I've added two garages that I'm renting around town. Fortunately, the
mayor of Los Angeles has come to my rescue. He discovered me, came out to the

25:01.300 --> 25:11.860
house, had four librarians come and look at everything, and they estimated there
are approximately 300,000 pieces in the collection. And the city of Los Angeles

25:11.860 --> 25:21.920
in the near future is going to create an actual museum. It won't just be a wing
of the library or anything of that sort, but an actual bonafide science fiction

25:21.920 --> 25:32.020
museum that already, when you're three blocks away, the structure of it will
tell the story. It's just, hey, that's got to be the museum. And the grandson of

25:32.020 --> 25:41.760
Edgar Rice Burroughs has already indicated to me when the museum exists, that
he'd be very happy to have an Edgar Rice Burroughs wing in it and make all of

25:41.760 --> 25:55.960
the first editions available and manuscripts and the artwork by J. Allen, St.
John and others. And I think that Hollywood will very much get into the act once

25:55.960 --> 26:07.540
it exists. And in addition to the props I've been able to acquire on my own,
